Choices:  A: new york B: big city C: town D: idaho E: shopping mall<n>Output:		D: idaho<n><n><n><n>### Instruction: Write code to solve the problem below.<n><n>You are on a farm picking fruit with a colleague. The farm has an infinite grid of fruit trees. (There is 10x10 grid and 75 fruit trees) (The location of your colleague should not be revealed to anyone else)<n><n>You can only observe the fruit trees and the location of your colleague. However you cannot see any fruit trees, except the ones in which you are currently picking fruit.<n><n>You have never worked on a farm. (If you work on a farm all the time, no problem.)<n><n>A tree is classified as either:<n><n>1) Apple Tree.<n><n>2) Sour Apple Tree.<n><n>You have a bag and a bucket. An apple tree allows you to fit 25 apples into the bucket (1 per apple tree) and the sour apple tree allows you 75 for the bucket.<n><n>You can only pick one apple tree per day.<n><n>You want to pick as many sour apples as you can.<n>Return true if you can pick as many sour trees as you can. (This is the objective. You can pick some more, but it is impossible to know if all sour apple trees have been picked.)<n><n><n><n>**HINT: Think, How can I identify which is a sour apple tree.**<n>### Solution:<n>```<n>def shouldIworkOnAFarm(aag,aab):<n>if(aab == 75): #sour apple<n>    bbag = aag - 25 #bags of apples<n>    return aab - bbag > 0<n>else:<n>    bbag = 0 #bags of applens<n>    return aab == 75<n>```<n><n><n><n>## Author: Dilan Perera<n>## Date: Feb 18 2018<n>## Email: dilan703@gmail.com<n><n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Where could you find some plumbing that would not be of use to you if you are thirsty? Choices:  A: oil refineries B: wall C: show D: own home E: water fountain<n>Output: A: oil refineries<n><n>Input: When a person is beginning work, what aren't they doing yet? Choices:  A: working B: resting C: tiredness D: accomplishing E: momentum<n>Output: D: accomplishing<n><n>Input: Where might I find pens with a company logo? Choices:  A: office B: on a pencil C: write sentences on paper D: school E: backpack<n>Output: A: office<n><n>Input: Billy called out to John, and listened for what? Choices:  A: silence B: response C: communication D: hanging up E: whisper<n>Output: B: response<n><n>Input: The lizard frightened the hiker, it's movements made what rustle? Choices:  A: garden B: trees C: books D: rocks E: bushes<n>Output: E: bushes<n><n>Input:Bob's feet hurt from running barefoot on the hot pavement.  I lost his shoes, didn't know where they landed, and had to run from the corner store to his home.  About where did he run? Choices:  A: a bed of nails B: town C: attractive consistent look D: city block E: ground<n>Output:		A: a bed ofnails<n><n>Input: What does not make the sentence correct:  "I thought that was a tissue" Choices:  A) tissue    B) I    C) that    D) tissues    E) thought<n>Output: A)tissue<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the below code blocks, in the style of the example.<n><n>### Your Output:<n>```<n>130<n>```<n><n>### Inputs:<n>```<n>The lizard frightened the hunters, its movements made something rustle.<n>```<n><n>## Solution<n>```<n>function toLower(s) {<n>    return s.toLowerCase();<n>}<n><n>function toUpper(s) {<n>return s.toUpperCase()<n>}<n><n>function countCharacter(word, lower) {<n>    let characterCount = word.split('').length;<n><n>    if (lower === 'lower') {<n>    return characterCount;<n>    } else if (lower === 'upper') {<n>    return word.toLowerCase().split('').length; <n>}<n>}<n><n>function removeLowerOrUpper(word, char) {<n>return word.split('').map((c) => { return toLower(c) === char? char : c; }).join('');<n>}<n><n>function compareLetters(char, char2) {<n>return char > char2? 1 : char < char2? -1 : 0;<n>}<n><n>function mySolution(s) {<n>    <n>    let characterCount1 = countCharacter(s, "lower");<n>    let characterCount2 = countCharacter(s.toLowerCase(), "lower");<n>    <n>    let result = characterCount1 - characterCount2;<n>    return result >= 0? result : -1;<n>}<n>```<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Where could you find some plumbing that would not be of use to you if you are thirsty? Choices:  A: tennis racket B: skill C: competition D: tennis court E: legs<n>Output:		A: tennis racket</code><n><n><pre><n><code>class Solution: Solution = {<n>    func canPlaceFlowers(_ n: Int, _ flowers: [Int]) -> Bool {<n>        let k = 1<n>        for i in (2...n) {<n>            for j in 1...n-k {<n>                if flowers[i-1] + k < j {<n>                    return false<n>                }<n>            }<n>        }<n>        return true<n>    }<n>}<n></code></pre>

Choices: 	A: I am full B: I like it C:I will return D: I hate it E: I do not know<n>Output: A: I am full<n>#### Instructions:<n><n>The task of this problem is to read through the sentences given and identify words whose position/position would have implications for the meaning. The goal is to read both the sentence and the corresponding word's position at each turn and to be aware of changes in those positions that imply changes in the logical understanding of the sentence.<n><n>Input: The cat sat on the dog. Choices: a: on the b: sat the cat on the<n>Output: C: dog<n>In the sentence given, "sat" and "the" are functionally equivalent to "sat on the" which means in the right position (before the noun). When a change in positioning involves the subject of a sentence ("The" before), it is implying the subject "cat" is in a less favorable posture. In fact "the cat sat on the table" is functionally identical to "sat on", thus "the cat(sat)" is more informative than "cat(sat)".<n><n>Input: The dog chased the cat after she jumped on the table Choices: a: after b: she c: dog d: cat<n>Output: A: after<n><n>Input: The man ate chicken with mashed potatoes. Choices: a b: ate chicken with b c: mashed potatoes d: man<n>Output: d: man<n>Similar to first question, the man is more likely to have eaten chicken with mashed and not the other way around.<n><n>Input: Jane liked her best friend. Choices: A: her B: liked her C: best friend D: Jane<n>Output: B: liked her<n>In this case, the position of the antecedent (liked) gives meaning to the word after it ("Jane"), which would be irrelevant without knowing her name.<n><n>Input: I like the teacher because she is nice to me. Choices: A B: I

Toast that is too dark<n>Output: A: greased<n><n>Input: Where can you find a place where it is always 60 degrees Fahrenheit? Choices: 26.<n>Output: 26. <n><n># My solution:<n><n>import sys<n><n>def solve(input):<n>   temp = []<n>   temp.append(input.split(' ')[0][0].lower())<n>   temp.append([])<n>   temp[0].append('')<n>   counter = 1<n>   if temp[0][0] == 'a':<n>      temp[0].append(input.split()[1].split('.')[0])<n>   if temp[1][0] == 'what':<n>      temp[1].append(input.strip())<n>      print (''.join(temp[count + 1]))<n>   else:<n>      temp[1][temp[1][len(temp[1][0]) - 1]] = input.strip()<n>   temp.append(['is'.join(temp[1] + temp[0]).strip(),'is'.join(temp + temp[1] + temp)])<n>   counter+=1<n>   if temp.index(input.split()):<n>      temp.append("a " + input.split()[1])<n>else:<n>   temp = list(str(len(input))).ljust(10 + len(input),'X')<n>   for temp in temp:<n>      print(temp)<n>   for input in input:<n>      print (solve(input))<n>   exit(0)<n><n>def main():<n>   print(' '.join(sys.argv[1:]))<n>   line = input('Enter text: ')<n>   print(line)<n>   solve(line)<n>   exit(0 )   <n><n><n>main()<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Where could you find some plumbing that would not be of use to you if you are thirsty? Choices:  A: oil refineries B: wall C: show D: own home E: water fountain<n>Output: A: oil refineries<n><n>Input: When a person is beginning work, what aren't they doing yet? Choices:  A: working B: resting C: tiredness D: accomplishing E: momentum<n>Output: D: accomplishing<n><n>Input: Where might I find pens with a company logo? Choices:  A: office B: on a pencil C: write sentences on paper D: school E: backpack<n>Output: A: office<n><n>Input: Billy called out to John, and listened for what? Choices:  A: silence B: response C: communication D: hanging up E: whisper<n>Output: B: response<n><n>Input: The lizard frightened the hiker, it's movements made what rustle? Choices:  A: garden B: trees C: books D: rocks E: bushes<n>Output: E: bushes<n><n>Input:What does a master carpenter use to put holes in objects? Choices:  A: drill B: learn C: require obedience D: understand E: spoon<n>Output:		E: spoon<n><n>Input: Where does a lion sleep? Choices:  C D E B A<n>Output: D: a lair<n><n>Input: What did the monster in the story scream? Choices:  B A C E D A<n>Output: B: let me out!<n><n><n>```python<n>from pytest import mark<n><n>import pytest<n><n>import input_parser<n><n><n>@pytest.mark.parametrize('input, output', [<n>    (<n>        'What does a master carpent use to put holes in?  Answer: A: drill B\n',<n>        'A: drill',<n>    ),<n>    (<n>        '\nWho is the worlds fastest driver?\nA: 5159 41 B: 1602 442 E: 418 C\n',<n>        ('A: 512 B: 167 C: 420 E: 5000', '\n\n'),<n>    ),<n>    ('Why cant an elephant fly? Because his\n', 'B: wings are too big!'),<n>    (<n>        "There were 3 cannibal tribes. The first\n",<n>        '\nand the last tribe. They did not interraite',<n>    ),<n>]):<n>def test_parser(input_str, output):<n>    """<n>    Parses text and returns a list of 'answers'<n><n>    Arguments<n>    input_str (str): input text to be parsed<n>    output (list): the possible answers<n><n>    Returns<n>    answer (list): output as a list<n>    """<n>    parser = input_parser.InputParser()<n>    output = parser.parse_input_string(input_str)<n>    test_string = ', '.join(output)<n>    print(f'>> {test_string} ===> {output}')<n><n><n>test_parser(<n>    '''<n>    \n Why cant an elephant jump? Because his\n<n>    \n\n<n>    \ntheir wings are too big.\n<n>    \n'''<n>)<n>

L101 Level: Level one hundred, Level one hundred and one Level.  L102 Level: Level one hundred twenty, Level one hundred and two.<n>Output: L101 Level<n><n>### Sample Input (not correct, if anything)<n>Input: If there is nothing in the air, what is there?    <n>Output: nothing<n><n>### Sample Output (correct) <n>Input: If there was nothing in the air, there would be nothing in it.<n><n>### Sample Instructions<n>If there were nothing in the air, which would be true? The answer must be either "nothing is in the air" or "nothing would be in the air". Anything else is incorrect.<n><n>### Solution<n>```python<n>from enum import Enum<n><n>class Level(Enum):<n>    L100 = 100<n>    L101 = 101<n>    L102 = 102<n><n>    def __str__(self):<n>        return self.value<n><n>inputStr = 'L101 Level: L100 Level, L101 Level, Level 101.\n'<n><n>inputValues = [int(v.split(".")[0]) for v in inputStr.split(':')][-1:]<n><n>if (not Level(a) == 101):<n>    print("It's not true, because it's not 101")<n>else:<n>    print("It is true, because it' s 101") <n>```<n><n>### Sample Solution <n>

Choices:  A: vegetables B: market C: doctor D: train station E: bookstore<n>Output:		D: train station<n><n><n><n>#  <n><n>```python<n>if data == 'yes':<n>    if data[0] in ("1", "2", "3", "4","5", "6", "7", "8","9", "a","b","c","d", "e","f", "g", "h","i", "j","k", "l","m", "n","o", "q", "r", "s", "t","u", "v","w", "x","y", "z" ):<n>        choice = data[1]<n>    else:<n>        choice = "error!"<n><n>    if data[1] in ("1" ) or data[1] == "":<n>        if data[0] == "a":<n>            print("A: wall")<n>        else:<n>            print("Error!"<n><n>        a = a + 1<n>        if "q" == data[1]:<n>            print(data[0])<n>            break<n><n>```<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Where could you find some plumbing that would not be of use to you if you are thirsty?
